article.description: Lisa Leslie's layup with 4.4 seconds to play gave the Los Angeles Sparks a 73-71 victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Los Angeles has won 9 of last 10
article.linkText: Leslie's late bucket lifts Sparks to No. 1 in West
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lisa Leslie gave her coach a dramatic
going-away present and her teammates first place in the WNBA's
Western Conference.

Leslie scored a layup with 4.4 seconds to play to give the Los
Angeles Sparks a 73-71 victory Wednesday night over the Phoenix
Mercury.

Leslie finished with 13 points and 12 rebounds. Mwadi Mabika
added 14 points as the Sparks (12-6) used their fourth consecutive
victory and ninth in 10 games to move into first place in the
WNBA's Western Conference.

The game was the final one at home for Los Angeles coach Michael
Cooper, who guided the Sparks to WNBA championships in 2001 and
2002. Cooper resigned Tuesday to become an assistant with the NBA's
Denver Nuggets.

"That's the Sparks that can win a championship, with or without
Michael Cooper," he said. "I know that with or without me,
they're going to continue to win and win another championship."

Diana Taurasi scored a game-high 25 points and Penny Taylor
added 22 points for the Mercury (8-9), which made 11-of-23 shots
from 3-point range.

Phoenix held a 71-69 lead when DeLisha Milton-Jones made a
jump shot with 59.7 seconds left to tie the score. With 25.3 seconds
to play, the Sparks' Laura Macchi stole the inbounds pass and
called a timeout.

Point guard Nikki Teasley found Leslie underneath the basket and
fired a 20-foot pass that Leslie converted into the winning basket.
Taurasi's 3-point shot at the buzzer missed.

"To get that close to Los Angeles on their home court, I think
we put out a pretty good effort," Mercury coach Carrie Graf said.
"We made some good runs and had a chance to win it at the end."

Phoenix used a 14-0 surge to turn a 55-43 deficit into a 57-55
lead with 8:53 to play. Taurasi scored the run's final eight
points.

The Sparks played without guard Tamecka Dixon, who suffered a
concussion Friday night after colliding with San Antonio's Margo
Dydek during an 87-80 overtime victory.

Phoenix released guard Edwina Brown, who had been on injured
reserve all season with Achilles tendon problems.
